Last year everything felt off. I believe everything that happened the last fews years personally and globally had finally caught up with me and I just felt lost. I was deeply struggling and felt like I lost my purpose. I didn’t feel like my usual self and that impacted every part of my life. I doubted myself in every capacity possible and desperately just wanted to feel “normal “again.  Some days it was so hard to get out of bed and some days it was hard to do absolutely anything at all. So today as I was going through comments and reading DMs, I came upon so many amazing messages that reminded me of why I started Female Collective in the first place. To create a safe space within the internet world when we’re feeling hopeless that helps reminds us that we are worthy of everything no matter what’s going on in our life, that there are people out there who are here to listen to you, and to remind you to be gentle with yourself. 

Life will have many highs and lows, and sometimes those lows will be VERY low, but the community I’ve been able to grow with the Female Collective will always be here to help inspire, uplift, grow, and heal with you. So this is a thank you to the Female Collective community for just supporting me every step of the way and reminding me of my purpose. Also a thank you to my family and friends for always being here for me in the simplest and purest ways. I feel really good about 2023 and I’m excited to see what the future holds, xo @candacereels

Growing up I didn’t always love the way I looked. There were times that I actually hated everything about myself. A lot of it had to do with Eurocentric beauty being shown in my face as the human standard of greatness. That if I didn’t have certain features I was seen and thought of as ugly. It took me all the way until my late 20s to know that wasn’t true. Also growing up I had this sense of pressure that I couldn’t make mistakes in life that I always had to be 10x better than my white counterparts to get an ounce of respect. All of these things and more took a toll on mental health. But as I’ve gotten older and started my healing journey I realized that being a Black woman is one of the most powerful things you can be. Yes, there are a lot of hardships that come our way for simply just being. But we’re also the ones that set the standard and we are the muse. Also that as Black women we don’t always need to be seen as strong, someone that can do everything on their own, and caretakers. We’re actually allowed to be soft, vulnerable, and to make mistakes. We’re allowed to serve ourselves. I’m saying all this because I just want all the young Black girls who are struggling to know that we as Black women are beautiful, multifaceted human beings that are worthy of everything we want in life.

Pride is important because someone today still believes they’re better off not being here than being themselves. Pride Month is not just a time to celebrate how far we’ve come, but also a time to acknowledge how far we have to go. With over 400 pieces of anti-LGBTQ+ legislation being floated around the U.S. we must continue to fight for every human to be able to be their true self. That is where real change happens when we as humans are not only allowed to be different, but celebrated for our many differences. That is why Pride month is so important it is a time to forge strong and supportive relationships where there is no judgement and we are just here to love and support one another.

As many of you know, I’m on the journey of finding my joy again in 2023. So what is it that brings me joy outside of the internet? What are daily things I can add to life that make me happy and help ground me not into the person I used to be but into the person I’m growing to be. I’m slowly answering those questions by prioritizing my health for the first time in a very long time and I’m easily able to do so with my @thenesscard. With Ness, I earn 5x points on purchases at health and wellness businesses and 2x points everywhere else. Then, you can use those points to redeem wellness brands, services, and experiences like Juice Press, Classpass, and Starface in the Ness App! By focusing on my self-improvement I’m able to stay present and truly take care of myself. This @thenesscard arrived at the perfect time as it’s been so vital to making sure I stay on top of my wellness journey so I can accomplish my mission of finding my joy again in 2023. #NessPartner

Juneteenth is a complicated holiday to say the least… in my opinion. As we know Juneteenth is a pivotal moment in our nation’s history. Today, we commemorate the news of emancipation reaching enslaved Black Americans in Galveston, Texas. While it is important to honor our ancestors' triumphs and sacrifices. It’s also important to acknowledge the ongoing struggles of Black Americans to be seen and treated as equal. Yes, we have come so far as Black Americans but there is still so much that can be done and we shouldn’t be afraid to demand for more. Society will make you feel like demanding more for yourself is selfish, when it should be our right to want the best for ourselves and families. All this to say to all of my non Black folks that follow me is to enjoy the day off but continue to educate yourself on our history, know that you have many privileges that can help people that look like me, don’t be afraid to be wrong in many situations, and just know that the world will be a much better place when we are all truly treated equally.

Voting has and will always be extremely important to me. From a young age my mom instilled in me just how important it was for me to vote being a black woman. I knew from then on that I would never take for granted my right to vote, as so many before me literally fought and die so I could easily take my ass to the polling place haha. When I turned 18, my parents and I had a big celebration of me finally being able to vote and since then I have voted in every big and small election. Today is National Voter Registration Day! So make sure you are registered to vote and if not register TODAY!! We have VERY important elections coming up this year and next!! I’ll continue to bug all of you hehe xx @candacereels #nationalvoterregistrationday

34, happy, and in Italy! Happy Birthday to me! Today I turn 34 and I’m greeting this new year of life with excitement! I’m learning to be gentle with myself. It’s ok to make mistakes. It’s ok to allow yourself to rest as there is no need to be productive every single moment of your life. As a perfectionist I am not easy on myself and I am my toughest critic. But this new year I want to my biggest supporter and celebrate every single moment of this crazy thing we call life. I’m lucky to be surrounded by incredible humans that continue to inspire, love, and support me. My birthday wish this year is that while life continues to be strange I want all of you to celebrate all of the goodness around you and allow yourself to have so much fun. #libraseason
